
This project analyzed a retail sales dataset containing over 323,000 transaction records. Data cleaning, exploratory data analysis, and business intelligence techniques were applied to identify revenue patterns and performance drivers.

Key findings revealed that Product P0129 generated the highest revenue among all products, while Store S0097 emerged as the best-performing store. Product Cluster_0 contributed the largest share of overall revenue, indicating strong customer demand within that segment. City C014 significantly outperformed other cities in terms of revenue generation.

Correlation analysis showed a strong positive relationship between sales and revenue, while price demonstrated minimal impact on revenue generation. Revenue distribution analysis indicated that most transactions generated low revenue, with a small number of high-value transactions contributing substantially to total revenue.

The insights generated from this analysis can help retailers optimize inventory planning, focus marketing efforts on high-performing product segments, and improve decision-making for store and city-level operations.
